    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Easily identified, flat-growing, spiky-leaved geophyte. The lobed leaves lie flat on the ground and emerge from a large tuberous root which exudes a sticky resin when broken. Each leaf has spiny margins and bears recurved thorns. Plants are either male or female, with male flowers cream and borne on stalks, while female flowers are green, stalkless and borne in a spiny head.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9345",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants up to about 6 cm tall, but up to 60 cm in diameter. Flower spikes up to 15 cm tall.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9346",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namaqualand to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9347",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Distinctive species found on damp sand and rocky areas both close to the coast and further inland. The spiny leaves are thought to provide protection against herbivores, and spines on the fruit may also aid dispersal by sticking to the fur of animals.</p><p>This species has a long history of use in traditional medicine. A decoction of the root has been used for treatment of a wide range of disorders including syphilis, gonorrhea, epilepsy, bladder ailments, glandular swellings, etc. The resin from the root may also be used to treat ringworm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9348",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9349",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers May to July. Separate male and female plants. Fruit dry, brown and spiny.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9350",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Easily recognised to genus by distinctive leaves and flowers. There are three regional species of which this is the most common. Could be confused with Hedgehog lilies <i>Massonia</i> spp. which also have large leaves that lie flat on the ground and a central clump of stemless flowers, but these are distantly-related bulbous plants and the leaves are tongue-shaped and either smooth or grooved, but not spiky.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9351",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
